    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hi, i'm trying to help my dad with some estate planning stuff. can u explain what \"durable power of attorney\" actually is? and how is it different from just a regular power of attorney? i want to make sure i understand it before we talk to his lawyer.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A durable power of attorney is a legal document that grants your dad the authority to make financial and legal decisions on his behalf, and crucially, it remains valid even if he loses his mental capacity or becomes incapacitated. In contrast, a regular (non-durable) power of attorney only lasts while your dad is mentally competent; if he loses his mind, that document automatically expires, leaving his affairs in limbo.\n\nThink of it like a trusty key that works for the entire duration of your dad's life, whereas a regular key only works while he is awake and able to use it. If your dad is in a coma or suffering from dementia, the regular key stops working, but the durable one keeps functioning, allowing you to manage his estate, pay bills, or handle medical decisions without needing a court-appointed guardian.\n\nYou might ask, \"What about the 'durable' part?\" The word \"durable\" is just a fancy way of saying \"won't break when things get tough.\" It's like a rubber band that stretches and snaps back; a regular power of attorney is like a stiff plastic ruler that snaps if you bend it too much.\n\nHere's a quick analogy: Imagine your dad is a captain of",
      "source": "target",
